stem: "Why is \`const\` required on \`const int MAX = 700;\`?"
source: 
  kind: "v2"
  ref: "v2:Q4 — Block A: const int MAX = N; (compile-time constant for array bound)"
commonMistakeIds: []
status: "NEW"
authoringStatus: "DRAFT"
createdBy: "SA-L4-Q4"
correct: "C++ requires the array bound to be a compile-time constant; \`const int\` qualifies, plain \`int\` does not."
distractors: 
  - "It is purely stylistic."
  - "It saves memory."
  - "It makes the program faster."
explanation: "const enables the compiler to use MAX in array bounds. Without const, the compiler treats MAX as a runtime variable."
